        d3f:OffensiveTactic,
        d3f:SPARTATacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Impact",
        "Threat actor is trying to manipulate, interrupt, or destroy the space system(s) and/or data." ;
    skos:editorialNote "Threat actor is trying to manipulate, interrupt, or destroy the space system(s) and/or data." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:ST0009 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:SemiSupervisedWrapperMethod a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Semi_supervisedWrapperMethod" ;
    d3f:d3fend-id "D3A-SSWM" ;
    d3f:kb-article "## References Jashish, M. (n.d.). Beginner's Guide to Semi-Supervised Learning. Jashish Blog. [Link](http://jashish.com.np/blog/posts/beginners-guide-to-semi-supervised-learning/)." ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Semi-supervised Wrapper Method" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:SemiSupervisedLearning ;
    skos:altLabel "Semi-supervisedWrapperMethod" ;
    skos:definition "The principle behind wrapper methods is that we train a model with labeled data and then generate pseudo-labels for the unlabeled data using the trained model iteratively." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:Semi-supervisedWrapperMethod ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:Session a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Session" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso dbr:Session_\(computer_science\),
        <https://schema.ocsf.io/objects/session> ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DigitalInformationBearer ;
    skos:closeMatch unified_cyber_ontology:UserSession ;
    skos:definition "In computer science, in particular networking, a session is a semi-permanent interactive information interchange, also known as a dialogue, a conversation or a meeting, between two or more communicating devices, or between a computer and user (see Login session). A session is set up or established at a certain point in time, and then torn down at some later point. An established communication session may involve more than one message in each direction. A session is typically, but not always, stateful, meaning that at least one of the communicating parts needs to save information about the session history in order to be able to communicate, as opposed to stateless communication, where the communication consists of independent requests with responses." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:Session ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:Shim a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Shim" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso dbr:Shim_\(computing\) ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:Software ;
    skos:definition "In computer programming, a shim is a small library that transparently intercepts API calls and changes the arguments passed, handles the operation itself, or redirects the operation elsewhere. Shims can be used to support an old API in a newer environment, or a new API in an older environment. Shims can also be used for running programs on different software platforms than those for which they were developed." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:Shim ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:Signal a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Signal" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso dbr:Signal ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:PhysicalArtifact ;
    skos:definition "In electronics and telecommunications, signal refers to any time-varying voltage, current, or electromagnetic wave that carries information." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:Signal ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:SoftwareClockEvent a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "SoftwareClockEvent" ;
    dcterms:title "Software Clock Event" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:ClockEvent ;
    skos:definition "A clock event involving a software-based timekeeping mechanism maintained by an operating system or application." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:SoftwareClockEvent ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:SoftwareDefinedRadioEvent a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Software_definedRadioEvent" ;
    d3f:synonym "SDR Event" ;
    dcterms:title "Software-defined Radio Event" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DigitalEvent ;
    skos:altLabel "Software-definedRadioEvent" ;
    skos:definition "An event involving a software-defined radio (SDR) device indicating that the SDR's lifecycle state, operational state, configuration, data-streaming status, timing/reference status, or fault condition has changed." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:Software-definedRadioEvent ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:SoftwarePackagingTool a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "SoftwarePackagingTool" ;
    dcterms:title "Software Packaging Tool" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso dbr:Build_automation,
        dbr:Package_manager ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:BuildTool ;
    skos:definition "A tool that automates the process of packaging either or both binary code  and source code for use on one or more target platforms." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:SoftwarePackagingTool ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:Storage a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Storage" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    d3f:synonym "Computer data storage" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso dbr:Computer_data_storage ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DigitalInformationBearer ;
    skos:definition "Computer data storage, often called storage or memory, is a technology consisting of computer components and recording media used to retain digital data. It is a core function and fundamental component of computers. In the Von Neumann architecture, the CPU consists of two main parts: The control unit and the arithmetic / logic unit (ALU). The former controls the flow of data between the CPU and memory, while the latter performs arithmetic and logical operations on data." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:Storage ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:StringPatternMatching a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "StringPatternMatching" ;
    d3f:d3fend-id "D3A-SPM" ;
    d3f:kb-article "## How it works A basic example of string searching is when the pattern and the searched text are arrays of elements of an alphabet (finite set) Σ. Σ may be a human language alphabet, for example, the letters A through Z and other applications may use a binary alphabet (Σ = {0,1}) or a DNA alphabet" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "String Pattern Matching" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:PatternMatching ;
    skos:definition "String pattern-matching algorithms, also known as string-matching algorithms, are an important class of string algorithms that try to find a place where one or several strings (also called patterns) are found within a larger string or text" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:StringPatternMatching ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:SupervisedLearning a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "SupervisedLearning" ;
    d3f:d3fend-id "D3A-SL" ;
    d3f:kb-article "## References Supervised learning. Wikipedia. [Link](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supervised_learning)." ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Supervised Learning" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:MachineLearning ;
    skos:definition "Supervised learning establishes a relationship between the known input and output variables to conduct a predictive analysis." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:SupervisedLearning ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:SymbolicLogic a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "SymbolicLogic" ;
    d3f:d3fend-id "D3A-SL" ;
    d3f:kb-article "## How it Works ## References 1. Symbolic Logic. (2023, June 6). In _Wolfram Mathworld_. [Link](https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SymbolicLogic.html) 2. Hughes, G. and Schagrin, M. (2023, Apr 19). Formal Logic. _Encyclopedia Brittanica_. [Link](https://www.britannica.com/topic/formal-logic) 3. Carnap," ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Symbolic Logic" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:AnalyticTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Symbolic Logic, also known as formal logic, is a branch of mathematics that uses symbolic representations for logical expressions and relationships. It provides a systematic method for examining the structure of arguments and reasoning, focusing on the relationships between propositions rather than the content of those propositions." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:SymbolicLogic ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:SystemConfigSystemCall a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "SystemConfigSystemCall" ;
    dcterms:title "System Config System Call" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:SystemCall ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:SystemConfigSystemCall ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:SystemSoftware a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "SystemSoftware" ;
    dcterms:title "System Software" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:Software ;
    skos:definition "Computer software which enables operating system or platform functionality." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:SystemSoftware ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1016 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1016" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1016" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "System Network Configuration Discovery" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DiscoveryTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may look for details about the network configuration and settings, such as IP and/or MAC addresses, of systems they access or through information discovery of remote systems. Several operating system administration utilities exist that can be used to gather this information. Examples include [Arp](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0099), [ipconfig](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0100)/[ifconfig](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0101), [nbtstat](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0102), and [route](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0103)." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1016,
        mitre-attack:T1016 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1132 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1132" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1132" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Data Encoding" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:CommandAndControlTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may encode data to make the content of command and control traffic more difficult to detect. Command and control (C2) information can be encoded using a standard data encoding system. Use of data encoding may adhere to existing protocol specifications and includes use of ASCII, Unicode, Base64, MIME, or other binary-to-text and character encoding systems.(Citation: Wikipedia Binary-to-text Encoding) (Citation: Wikipedia Character Encoding) Some data encoding systems may also result in data compression, such as gzip." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1132,
        mitre-attack:T1132 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1176 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1176" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1176" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Software Extensions" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:PersistenceTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may abuse Internet browser extensions to establish persistent access to victim systems. Browser extensions or plugins are small programs that can add functionality and customize aspects of Internet browsers. They can be installed directly or through a browser's app store and generally have access and permissions to everything that the browser can access.(Citation: Wikipedia Browser Extension)(Citation: Chrome Extensions Definition)" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1176,
        mitre-attack:T1176 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1216 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1216" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1216" ;
    dcterms:title "System Script Proxy Execution" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DefenseEvasionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may use trusted scripts, often signed with certificates, to proxy the execution of malicious files. Several Microsoft signed scripts that have been downloaded from Microsoft or are default on Windows installations can be used to proxy execution of other files.(Citation: LOLBAS Project) This behavior may be abused by adversaries to execute malicious files that could bypass application control and signature validation on systems.(Citation: GitHub Ultimate AppLocker Bypass List)" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1216,
        mitre-attack:T1216 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1222 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1222" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1222" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "File and Directory Permissions Modification" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DefenseEvasionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may modify file or directory permissions/attributes to evade access control lists (ACLs) and access protected files.(Citation: Hybrid Analysis Icacls1 June 2018)(Citation: Hybrid Analysis Icacls2 May 2018) File and directory permissions are commonly managed by ACLs configured by the file or directory owner, or users with the appropriate permissions. File and directory ACL implementations vary by platform, but generally explicitly designate which users or groups can perform which actions (read, write, execute, etc.)." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1222,
        mitre-attack:T1222 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1406 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1406" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1406" ;
    dcterms:title "Obfuscated Files or Information" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:ATTACKMobileDefenseEvasionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may attempt to make a payload or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the device or in transit. This is common behavior that can be used across different platforms and the network to evade defenses." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1406,
        mitre-attack:T1406 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1417 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1417" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1417" ;
    dcterms:title "Input Capture" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:ATTACKMobileCredentialAccessTechnique ],
        d3f:ATTACKMobileCollectionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information. During normal device usage, users often provide credentials to various locations, such as login pages/portals or system dialog boxes. Input capture mechanisms may be transparent to the user (e.g. [Keylogging](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1417/001)) or rely on deceiving the user into providing input into what they believe to be a genuine application prompt (e.g. [GUI Input Capture](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1417/002))." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1417,
        mitre-attack:T1417 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1422 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1422" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1422" ;
    dcterms:title "System Network Configuration Discovery" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:ATTACKMobileDiscoveryTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may look for details about the network configuration and settings, such as IP and/or MAC addresses, of devices they access or through information discovery of remote systems." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1422,
        mitre-attack:T1422 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1430 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1430" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1430" ;
    dcterms:title "Location Tracking" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:ATTACKMobileDiscoveryTechnique ],
        d3f:ATTACKMobileCollectionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may track a device’s physical location through use of standard operating system APIs via malicious or exploited applications on the compromised device." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1430,
        mitre-attack:T1430 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1480 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1480" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1480" ;
    dcterms:title "Execution Guardrails" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DefenseEvasionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may use execution guardrails to constrain execution or actions based on adversary supplied and environment specific conditions that are expected to be present on the target. Guardrails ensure that a payload only executes against an intended target and reduces collateral damage from an adversary’s campaign.(Citation: FireEye Kevin Mandia Guardrails) Values an adversary can provide about a target system or environment to use as guardrails may include specific network share names, attached physical devices, files, joined Active Directory (AD) domains, and local/external IP addresses.(Citation: FireEye Outlook Dec 2019)" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1480,
        mitre-attack:T1480 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1484 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1484" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1484" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Domain or Tenant Policy Modification" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:PrivilegeEscalationTechnique ],
        d3f:DefenseEvasionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may modify the configuration settings of a domain or identity tenant to evade defenses and/or escalate privileges in centrally managed environments. Such services provide a centralized means of managing identity resources such as devices and accounts, and often include configuration settings that may apply between domains or tenants such as trust relationships, identity syncing, or identity federation." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1484,
        mitre-attack:T1484 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1597 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1597" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1597" ;
    dcterms:title "Search Closed Sources" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:ReconnaissanceTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may search and gather information about victims from closed sources that can be used during targeting. Information about victims may be available for purchase from reputable private sources and databases, such as paid subscriptions to feeds of technical/threat intelligence data.(Citation: D3Secutrity CTI Feeds) Adversaries may also purchase information from less-reputable sources such as dark web or cybercrime blackmarkets.(Citation: ZDNET Selling Data)" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1597,
        mitre-attack:T1597 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1600 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1600" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1600" ;
    dcterms:title "Weaken Encryption" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DefenseEvasionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may compromise a network device’s encryption capability in order to bypass encryption that would otherwise protect data communications. (Citation: Cisco Synful Knock Evolution)" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1600,
        mitre-attack:T1600 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1601 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1601" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1601" ;
    dcterms:title "Modify System Image" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:DefenseEvasionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may make changes to the operating system of embedded network devices to weaken defenses and provide new capabilities for themselves.  On such devices, the operating systems are typically monolithic and most of the device functionality and capabilities are contained within a single file." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1601,
        mitre-attack:T1601 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1602 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1602" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1602" ;
    dcterms:title "Data from Configuration Repository" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:CollectionTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may collect data related to managed devices from configuration repositories. Configuration repositories are used by management systems in order to configure, manage, and control data on remote systems. Configuration repositories may also facilitate remote access and administration of devices." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1602,
        mitre-attack:T1602 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:T1606 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "T1606" ;
    d3f:attack-id "T1606" ;
    dcterms:title "Forge Web Credentials" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf d3f:CredentialAccessTechnique ;
    skos:definition "Adversaries may forge credential materials that can be used to gain access to web applications or Internet services. Web applications and services (hosted in cloud SaaS environments or on-premise servers) often use session cookies, tokens, or other materials to authenticate and authorize user access." ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:T1606,
        mitre-attack:T1606 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0001 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0001" ;
    d3f:display-order "1" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Initial Access" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Initial Access",
        """The adversary is trying to get into your network.

Initial Access consists of techniques that use various entry vectors to gain their initial foothold within a network. Techniques used to gain a foothold include targeted spearphishing and exploiting weaknesses on public-facing web servers. Footholds gained through initial access may allow for continued access, like valid accounts and use of external remote services, or may be limited-use due to changing passwords.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to get into your network. Initial Access consists of techniques that use various entry vectors to gain their initial foothold within a network. Techniques used to gain a foothold include targeted spearphishing and exploiting weaknesses on public-facing web servers. Footholds gained through initial access may allow for continued access, like valid accounts and use of extern" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0001 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0002 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0002" ;
    d3f:display-order "2" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Execution" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Execution",
        """The adversary is trying to run malicious code.

Execution consists of techniques that result in adversary-controlled code running on a local or remote system. Techniques that run malicious code are often paired with techniques from all other tactics to achieve broader goals, like exploring a network or stealing data. For example, an adversary might use a remote access tool to run a PowerShell script that does Remote System Discovery.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to run malicious code. Execution consists of techniques that result in adversary-controlled code running on a local or remote system. Techniques that run malicious code are often paired with techniques from all other tactics to achieve broader goals, like exploring a network or stealing data. For example, an adversary might use a remote access tool to run a PowerShell scri" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0002 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0003 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0003" ;
    d3f:display-order "3" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Persistence" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Persistence",
        """The adversary is trying to maintain their foothold.

Persistence consists of techniques that adversaries use to keep access to systems across restarts, changed credentials, and other interruptions that could cut off their access. Techniques used for persistence include any access, action, or configuration changes that let them maintain their foothold on systems, such as replacing or hijacking legitimate code or adding startup code.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to maintain their foothold. Persistence consists of techniques that adversaries use to keep access to systems across restarts, changed credentials, and other interruptions that could cut off their access. Techniques used for persistence include any access, action, or configuration changes that let them maintain their foothold on systems, such as replacing or hijacking legi" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0003 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0004 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0004" ;
    d3f:display-order "4" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Privilege Escalation" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Privilege Escalation",
        """The adversary is trying to gain higher-level permissions.

Privilege Escalation consists of techniques that adversaries use to gain higher-level permissions on a system or network. Adversaries can often enter and explore a network with unprivileged access but require elevated permissions to follow through on their objectives. Common approaches are to take advantage of system weaknesses, misconfigurations, and vulnerabilities. Examples of elevated access include:

SYSTEM/root level
local administrator
user account with admin-like access
user accounts with access to specific system or perform specific function

These techniques often overlap with Persistence techniques, as OS features that let an adversary persist can execute in an elevated context.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to gain higher-level permissions. Privilege Escalation consists of techniques that adversaries use to gain higher-level permissions on a system or network. Adversaries can often enter and explore a network with unprivileged access but require elevated permissions to follow through on their objectives. Common approaches are to take advantage of system weaknesses, misconfigu" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0004 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0005 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0005" ;
    d3f:display-order "5" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Defense Evasion" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Defense Evasion",
        """The adversary is trying to avoid being detected.

Defense Evasion consists of techniques that adversaries use to avoid detection throughout their compromise. Techniques used for defense evasion include uninstalling/disabling security software or obfuscating/encrypting data and scripts. Adversaries also leverage and abuse trusted processes to hide and masquerade their malware. Other tactics' techniques are cross-listed here when those techniques include the added benefit of subverting defenses.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to avoid being detected. Defense Evasion consists of techniques that adversaries use to avoid detection throughout their compromise. Techniques used for defense evasion include uninstalling/disabling security software or obfuscating/encrypting data and scripts. Adversaries also leverage and abuse trusted processes to hide and masquerade their malware. Other tactics' techni" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0005 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0006 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0006" ;
    d3f:display-order "6" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Credential Access" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Credential Access",
        """The adversary is trying to steal account names and passwords.

Credential Access consists of techniques for stealing credentials like account names and passwords. Techniques used to get credentials include keylogging or credential dumping. Using legitimate credentials can give adversaries access to systems, make them harder to detect, and provide the opportunity to create more accounts to help achieve their goals.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to steal account names and passwords. Credential Access consists of techniques for stealing credentials like account names and passwords. Techniques used to get credentials include keylogging or credential dumping. Using legitimate credentials can give adversaries access to systems, make them harder to detect, and provide the opportunity to create more accounts to help ach" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0006 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0007 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0007" ;
    d3f:display-order "7" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Discovery" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Discovery",
        """The adversary is trying to figure out your environment.

Discovery consists of techniques an adversary may use to gain knowledge about the system and internal network. These techniques help adversaries observe the environment and orient themselves before deciding how to act. They also allow adversaries to explore what they can control and what's around their entry point in order to discover how it could benefit their current objective. Native operating system tools are often used toward this post-compromise information-gathering objective.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to figure out your environment. Discovery consists of techniques an adversary may use to gain knowledge about the system and internal network. These techniques help adversaries observe the environment and orient themselves before deciding how to act. They also allow adversaries to explore what they can control and what's around their entry point in order to discover how it" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0007 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0008 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0008" ;
    d3f:display-order "8" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Lateral Movement" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Lateral Movement",
        """The adversary is trying to move through your environment.

Lateral Movement consists of techniques that adversaries use to enter and control remote systems on a network. Following through on their primary objective often requires exploring the network to find their target and subsequently gaining access to it. Reaching their objective often involves pivoting through multiple systems and accounts to gain. Adversaries might install their own remote access tools to accomplish Lateral Movement or use legitimate credentials with native network and operating system tools, which may be stealthier.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to move through your environment. Lateral Movement consists of techniques that adversaries use to enter and control remote systems on a network. Following through on their primary objective often requires exploring the network to find their target and subsequently gaining access to it. Reaching their objective often involves pivoting through multiple systems and accounts t" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0008 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0009 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0009" ;
    d3f:display-order "9" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Collection" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Collection",
        """The adversary is trying to gather data of interest to their goal.

Collection consists of techniques adversaries may use to gather information and the sources information is collected from that are relevant to following through on the adversary's objectives. Frequently, the next goal after collecting data is to either steal (exfiltrate) the data or to use the data to gain more information about the target environment. Common target sources include various drive types, browsers, audio, video, and email. Common collection methods include capturing screenshots and keyboard input.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to gather data of interest to their goal. Collection consists of techniques adversaries may use to gather information and the sources information is collected from that are relevant to following through on the adversary's objectives. Frequently, the next goal after collecting data is to either steal (exfiltrate) the data or to use the data to gain more information about th" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0009 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0010 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0010" ;
    d3f:display-order "11" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Exfiltration" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Exfiltration",
        """The adversary is trying to steal data.

Exfiltration consists of techniques that adversaries may use to steal data from your network. Once they've collected data, adversaries often package it to avoid detection while removing it. This can include compression and encryption. Techniques for getting data out of a target network typically include transferring it over their command and control channel or an alternate channel and may also include putting size limits on the transmission.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to steal data. Exfiltration consists of techniques that adversaries may use to steal data from your network. Once they've collected data, adversaries often package it to avoid detection while removing it. This can include compression and encryption. Techniques for getting data out of a target network typically include transferring it over their command and control channel" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0010 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

d3f:TA0011 a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "TA0011" ;
    d3f:display-order "10" ;
    d3f:owl_named_individual "true" ;
    dcterms:title "Command And Control" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty linkml:mixins ;
            owl:someValuesFrom d3f:OffensiveTactic ],
        d3f:ATTACKEnterpriseTactic,
        d3f:OffensiveTacticEnum,
        linkml:PermissibleValue ;
    skos:definition "Command And Control",
        """The adversary is trying to communicate with compromised systems to control them.

Command and Control consists of techniques that adversaries may use to communicate with systems under their control within a victim network. Adversaries commonly attempt to mimic normal, expected traffic to avoid detection. There are many ways an adversary can establish command and control with various levels of stealth depending on the victim's network structure and defenses.""" ;
    skos:editorialNote "The adversary is trying to communicate with compromised systems to control them. Command and Control consists of techniques that adversaries may use to communicate with systems under their control within a victim network. Adversaries commonly attempt to mimic normal, expected traffic to avoid detection. There are many ways an adversary can establish command and control with various levels of stea" ;
    skos:exactMatch d3f:TA0011 ;
    skos:inScheme <https://d3fend.mitre.org/ontologies/d3fend.owl> .

